[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(23, 24) The sons of half-Manasseh “in the land” east of Jordan. The translation should be: “And the children . . . dwelt in the land, from Bashan unto Baal-hermon and Senir and mount Hermon. These were many.” Their territory extended from “Bashan,” the domain of Gad, in the south, to the mountains of Hermon, or Antilibanus, in the north.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(23) Baal-hermon.—Perhaps the same as Baal-gad (Joshua 12:7; Joshua 13:5), the modern town of Banias.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(23) ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Baal-hermon.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Perhaps the same as Baal-gad (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Joshua 12:7",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Joshua 13:5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), the modern town of ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Banias.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Senir.—The Amorite name of the range of Hermon (Deuteronomy 3:9). The principal summit is now called Jebel esh-Sheikh, “hill of the chief,” and Jebel eth-Thelj, “Snow Hill.”",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Senir.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The Amorite name of the range of Hermon (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 3:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). The principal summit is now called ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Jebel esh-Sheikh, “",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "hill of the chief,” and ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Jebel eth-Thelj,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " “Snow Hill.”",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
