  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 23, 24.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - \"The half-tribe of Manasseh\" is here very briefly treated cf. Manasseh and his brother Ephraim stand in the place of Joseph, both the children of Joseph's Egyptian wife, Asenath, and born before the famine. Though Manasseh was the elder, Jacob gave the chief blessing (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 48:10-22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") to Ephraim. The Manassites were descended from Manasseh through his son Machir, born of a Syrian concubine (Septuagint, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 46:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 1:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26:28-34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 17:1-3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 7:14, 15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Machir evidently was ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "spes gregis",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (though apparently not the only son, for see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Asriel",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Ashriel",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in above references), and is repeatedly mentioned with his sou Gilead. It is probable that the division of the tribe was determined partly according to the energy of those who composed it at the time of division - the more warlike being more adapted to the east of Jordan. Nevertheless Machir is distinctly mentioned westward, as well as with Gilead eastward (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 5:14-17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 13:29-31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). (For the further prosecution of this part of the subject, see Exposition, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 7:14-19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 23.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Baal-hermon",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. These three names need scarcely be read as different names for exactly the same region, but as designating different sides or heights of what was essentially one and the same well-known mountain district, with which would agree Psalm 43:6, \"Therefore will I remember thee from the land of Jordan and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "of the Hermonites",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", from the hill Mizar.' So ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:8-10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " tells us that Hermon was called ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Sirion",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " by the Sidonians; Shenir, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.q. Senir",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "i.q. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "cmt_word",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Senir",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "שְׂנִיר",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", exactly the same word in the Hebrew text in all the four places of its occurrence - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Song of Solomon 4:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 27:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), by the Amorites. And the suggestion of Grove is likely enough, that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Baal-hermon",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " was the Phoenician cast of the name. If any point were to be gained by reading the names, however, as intended to cover exactly the same tract, it may be noted ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
